===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|spade}}, from {{inh|en|ang|spada}}, {{m|ang|spade}}, {{m|ang|spadu|t=spade}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*spadô}}. {{doublet|en|spatha|spathe|épée}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[garden]] [[tool]] with a handle and a flat [[blade]] for [[dig]]ging. Not to be confused with a [[shovel]] which is used for moving earth or other materials.
#* {{RQ:Falkner Moonfleet|year=1934|passage='Make your mind easy,' Ratsey said; 'I have dug too often in this graveyard for any to wonder if they see me with a '''spade'''.'}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2021 October 6|author=Paul Stephen|title=Network News: Labour: build HS2 and NPR and end "paper promises"|journal=RAIL|issue=941|page=25|text="[...] And not a single '''spade''' has gone in the ground - not a single mile of track built."}}
# A cutting instrument used in [[flense|flensing]] a [[whale]].
# {{lb|en|electrical engineering}} A device for terminating an electrical [[conductor]] resembling a small spade.

